U=\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp(-\rho t)C(t)dt
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each individual is endowed with one unit of labor that it supplies to the
 market inelastically.
 Individuals have access to a short-term risk-free bond market, with exogenous
 interest rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Individuals can also form intermediate goods firms (described below).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Individuals consume a unique final good 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(t)$
\end_inset

.
 The final good is produced by labor and a continuum of intermediate goods
 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 with production technology
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Requiring labor input for the final good simplifies the computation of equilibri
um.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y(t)=\frac{L^{\beta}(t)}{1-\beta}\int_{0}^{1}q_{j}^{\beta}(t)k_{j}^{1-\beta}(t)dj
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{j}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the quantity of the intermediate good 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q(t)$
\end_inset

 is its quality.
 Normalize the price of the final good 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(t)$
\end_inset

 to be one in every period without loss of generality.
 The final good is produced competitively with input prices taken as given.
 From now on, the time index 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 will be supressed where it causes no confusion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of incumbent firms [
\series bold
UNDERSTAND THIS!!! Check Acemoglu's textbook] 
\series default
producing intermediate goods in equilibrium
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Don't know if it's necessary to talk about the measure 
