\begin_layout Subsection
Research & Development
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Incumbent R&D
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Incumbent firms undertake R&D to improve the quality of the product they
 sell.
 A successful R&D project on product 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 renders its owner an incumbent producing product 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 with quality 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+\lambda)q_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}=\int_{0}^{m_{j}}z_{l}dl+z_{I}$
\end_inset

 as the total innovation effort undertaken on product 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Innovation effort 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 requires 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 units of R&D labor, and generates innovations at rate
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{I}(z;\overline{z})=\chi_{I}z\phi(\overline{z})
\]

\end_inset

To capture the net effect of all congestion and agglomeration externalities,
 we introduce the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 of total innovation effort.
 In general this could have any form to reflect these externalities; here,
 to keep the model simple, we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is decreasing, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{z\to0}\phi(z)=+\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{z\to\infty}\phi(z)=0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\overline{z})=\overline{z}^{\psi-1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi<1.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Entrant R&D
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The R&D technology for entrants differs only in the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{E}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This constant is only introduced to increase the quantitative flexibility
 of the model.
 Even with 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{E}=\chi_{I}$
\end_inset

, incumbents invest in R&D effort when there are no entrants (due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{z\to0}\phi(z)=+\infty$
\end_inset

), and eventually stop innovation effort as more and more R&D startups are
 formed.
 (This is another prediction of my model which could be used to discipline
 the model).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{E}(z;\overline{z})=\chi_{E}z\phi(\overline{z})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that entrants are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and do not take into account their effect on decreasing returns to R&D
 in the sector.
 To pin down the size of an individual entrant, assume that each startup
 can hire at most 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi>0$
\end_inset

 units of R&D labor.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}=\int_{0}^{m_{j}}z_{l}dl+z_{I}=\xi m_{j}+z_{I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, when the R&D technology becomes public, entry occurs until 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 reaches the value 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{t}(q)$
\end_inset

 at which entrants make zero profits in expectation.
 It can be shown that 
\end_layout

