\begin_layout Subsection
Non-competes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the version of the model with non-competes, workers will be unable to
 spin-out until 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

 years after leaving employment at their employer.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For tractability, will actually assume a Poisson process 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shocks
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the workers out of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

employment restricted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 status.
 Calibrate this shock so that the average non-compete is 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

 years long.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 During this time, the worker can work in any other industry but not the
 industry he was previously working at.
 However, there is a significant probability that the knowledge will become
 fully public, reducing the payoff to potentially attaining knowledge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[
\series bold
FIX HJBS TO TAKE INTO ACCOUNT NEW R&D FUNCTION 
\series default
- see stuff in notebook about finding the root of the FOC, need to use numeric
 method, but looks like objective is monotonic so can simply do binary search
 to find the zero]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 denote the (exogenous) rate at which knowledge enters the public domain
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}_{E}^{t}(q_{j},m_{j})$
\end_inset

 denote the (endogenous) rate at which a new spinoff is formed in product
 line 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, given the efforts of the mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 of potential entrants.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}(q_{j})$
\end_inset

 denote the time-
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 flow profit to an incumbent with quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 (given optimal monopolistic competition pricing).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}(q_{j},m_{j})$
\end_inset

 denote the time-
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 value of a frontier firm producing a good of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 and mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 of potential entrants
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In general, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 would also depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 only affects the value through 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 so we can drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 superscript on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and write simply 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}(q,m)$
\end_inset

.
 Later, we will normalize by the average quality level in the economy and
 show that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}(q,m)=Q_{t}A(q/Q_{t},m)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the HJB 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\big(r+\theta+\tau_{t}(q,m)\big)A_{t}(q,m) & = & \max_{z}\pi_{t}(q)+\theta B_{t}(q)+z\phi(z+\overline{z}_{E})\Big[A_{t}((1+\lambda)q,0)-A_{t}(q,m)\Big]\\
 &  & +\nu(\overline{z}_{E}(q,m)+z)\partial_{m}A_{t}(q,m)-w_{t}(q,m)z+\partial_{t}A_{t}(q,m)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}(q_{j})$
\end_inset

 denote the (endogenous) rate at which startups are formed once knowledge
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 is in the public domain.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t}(q_{j})$
\end_inset

 denote the time-
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 value of a quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 frontier firm whose knowledge has entered the public domain.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}$
\end_inset

 denote the wage paid to R&D labor when the knowledge has entered the public
 domain (this will be equal to the final goods wage in equilibrium, due
 to indifference condition).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t}(q)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the HJB 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\big(r+\sigma_{t}(q)\big)B_{t}(q)=\pi_{t}(q)+\partial_{t}B_{t}(q)+\max_{z}z\phi(\overline{z}_{E}+z)[A_{t}((1+\lambda)q,0)-B_{t}(q)]-w_{t}z
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maximization in the final goods sector and by the producers yields (see
 AK) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{t}=\tilde{\beta}\overline{q}_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\beta}\equiv\beta^{\beta}[1-\beta]^{1-2\beta}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Individuals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because individuals simply maximize the present-value of their consumption,
 and because their wages from supplying labor do not depend on their entrepreneu
rial efforts, we can simply think of the behavior of individuals as resulting
 from the separate maximization of the utilization of their various forms
 of capital: their time and their knowledge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Individuals supply labor to production of the intermediate goods as well
 as to R&D.
 Therefore, the flow value that a worker receives from R&D employment must
 be equal to the wage rate for intermediate goods production,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{t}=\tilde{\beta}\overline{q}_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Spin-outs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 denote the value to an individual of having acquired the technology to
 form a spin-out in a machine line of current quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and mass of competing entrants 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, but bound by a non-compete agreement.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{F}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 denote the value to an individual once the non-compete has expired (
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Free-agent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Individuals flow out of competition restriction at instantaneous Poisson
 rate 
\begin_inset Formula $v=1/T_{c}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This ensures that the average length of a non-compete is 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

 years.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall that ideas enter the public domain at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and are improved upon at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{t}(q,m)$
\end_inset

.
 In both of these events, the value to an individual with the technology
 goes to zero: in the former case, due to free entry; in the latter case,
 due to Assumption 1.
 Further, recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{m}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{j}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{t}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 denote the equilibrium labor allocation.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the HJB 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(r+\theta+\tau_{t}(q,m)+v)W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)=vW_{t}^{F}(q,m)+\partial_{m}W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)\hat{L}_{t}(q,m)+\partial_{t}W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I assume that R&D workers employed by spin-outs learn at the same rate as
 those employed by incumbents.
 Therefore they earn the same wage 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 whether employed by incumbents or spin-outs.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{F}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the HJB 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\big(r+\theta+\tau_{t}(q,m)\big)W_{t}^{F}(q,m) & = & \max_{z}\Big\{ z\big[A_{t}((1+\lambda)q,0)-W_{t}^{F}(q,m)\big]-w_{t}(q,m)R_{E}(z)\Big\}\\
 &  & +\partial_{m}W_{t}^{F}(q,m)\nu(\hat{L}_{t}(q,m)+mL_{t}^{E}(q,m))+\partial_{t}W_{t}^{F}(q,m)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{E}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 is the argmax.
 Note that, in contrast with the incumbent, individual spin-out does not
 take into account the effect of its level of employment on the spillovers
 of knowledge.
 This is because each individual spin-out is infinitesimal relative to the
 entire mass of spin-outs or to the mass of the incumbent.
 
\series bold
[make sure this makes sense].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effective flow wage received by a worker, including the flow value of
 the possibility of acquiring valuable knowledge, is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w(q,m)+\nu W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to Inada conditions on the R&D technology, we know we will have an interior
 solution.
 Therefore workers must be indifferent between supplying R&D to each type,
 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{t}(q,m)+\nu W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)=\tilde{\beta}\overline{q}_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
BGP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}=q/\overline{q}.$
\end_inset

 In this section, I look for a balanced growth path with a stationary joint
 distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

; where policies are functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 and invariant over time
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hence so are endogenous variables such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{t}(q,m)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

; and where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, wages, and value functions all grow at exponential rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}(q)=\pi q$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we are on a BGP with growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t}(q)=e^{gt}\tilde{B}(\tilde{q})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{t}e^{gt}\tilde{B}(e^{-gt}q)=ge^{gt}\tilde{B}(\tilde{q})-ge^{gt}\tilde{q}\tilde{B}'(\tilde{q})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the HJB becomes, after dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{gt}$
\end_inset

 and rearranging,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\overbrace{(r+\sigma(\tilde{q})-g)}^{\text{Effective discount factor}}\tilde{B}(\tilde{q}) & = & \underbrace{\pi\tilde{q}}_{\text{Flow profits}}-\underbrace{g\tilde{q}\tilde{B}'(\tilde{q})}_{\text{Obsolescence}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}(q,m)=e^{gt}\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{t}e^{gt}\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)]=ge^{gt}\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)-ge^{gt}\tilde{q}\partial_{q}\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the HJB becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\big(r+\theta+\tau(\tilde{q},m)-g\big)\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m) & = & \overbrace{\pi\tilde{q}}^{\text{Flow profit}}+\overbrace{\theta\tilde{B}(\tilde{q})}^{\text{Knowledge becomes public}}-\overbrace{g\tilde{q}\partial_{q}\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)}^{\text{Obsolescence}}\\
 &  & +\max_{z}\Big\{\underbrace{z\big[\tilde{A}((1+\lambda)\tilde{q},0)-\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)\big]}_{\text{Expected flow capital gain from R\&D}}\\
 &  & +\underbrace{\partial_{m}\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)(\nu R_{I}(z)+L_{E}^{R}(\tilde{q},m))}_{\text{Knowledge spillover cost of R\&D}}-\underbrace{w(\tilde{q},m)R_{I}(z)}_{\text{Direct cost of R\&D}}\Big\}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, consider the value function 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{NC}(q,m),W_{t}^{F}(q,m).$
\end_inset

 Supposing 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)=e^{gt}\tilde{W}^{NC}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{F}(q,m)=e^{gt}\tilde{W}^{F}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

, have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\partial_{t}[e^{gt}W^{NC}(e^{-gt}q,m)] & = & ge^{gt}W^{NC}(e^{-gt}q,m)-ge^{gt}\tilde{q}\partial_{\tilde{q}}W^{NC}(e^{-gt}q,m)\\
\partial_{t}[e^{gt}W^{F}(e^{-gt}q,m)] & = & ge^{gt}W^{F}(e^{-gt}q,m)-ge^{gt}\tilde{q}\partial_{\tilde{q}}W^{F}(e^{-gt}q,m)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The HJBs become
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
(r+\theta+\tau(\tilde{q},m)+v-g)\tilde{W}^{NC}(\tilde{q},m) & = & \overbrace{v\tilde{W}^{F}(\tilde{q},m)}^{\text{Expiry of non-compete}}+\overbrace{\partial_{m}\tilde{W}^{NC}(\tilde{q},m)\nu L^{R}(\tilde{q},m)}^{\text{Loss of rents due to knowledge spillovers}}\\
 &  & -\underbrace{g\tilde{q}\partial_{\tilde{q}}\tilde{W}^{NC}(\tilde{q},m)}_{\text{Obsolescence}}\\
(r+\theta+\tau(\tilde{q},m)-g)\tilde{W}^{F}(\tilde{q},m) & = & \overbrace{\max_{z}\Big\{ z\big[\tilde{A}((1+\lambda)\tilde{q},0)-\tilde{W}^{F}(\tilde{q},m)\big]-w(\tilde{q},m)R_{E}(z)\Big\}}^{\text{(Net) flow value from R\&D}}\\
 &  & +\underbrace{\partial_{m}\tilde{W}^{F}(\tilde{q},m)\nu(z+L_{E}^{R}(\tilde{q},m)}_{\text{Loss of rents due to knowledge spillovers}}-\underbrace{g\tilde{q}\partial_{\tilde{q}}\tilde{W}^{F}(\tilde{q},m)}_{\text{Obsolescence}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Stationary joint distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is clearly no stationary distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 But maybe of 
\begin_inset Formula $q/Q$
\end_inset

? Even then, not clear - it could spread out over time due to memorylessness.
 But whatever, just try to calculate, given 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta,\tau_{t},z_{I}(q,m),z_{E}(q,m),\tilde{z}_{E}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{z}_{E}$
\end_inset

 is the rate of innovation by entrants once the idea is in the public domain).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quantitative Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Computer Algorithm 1 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I solve the model as a fixed point over 
\begin_inset Formula $g,L^{F},\overline{z}_{E}(\tilde{q},m),\overline{z}_{E}^{0}(\tilde{q})$
\end_inset

.
 [MAY NEED TO ADD ANOTHER aggregate variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{E}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 because it affects rate of drift in 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 direction].
 The computational loop has the following steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Guess 
\begin_inset Formula $g,L^{F},\overline{z}_{E}(\tilde{q},m),\overline{z}_{E}^{0}(\tilde{q})$
\end_inset

.
 Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\tilde{q})=\pi\tilde{q}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=\pi(L^{F};\text{parameters})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{I}^{A}(\tilde{q},m),A(\tilde{q},m),z_{I}^{B}(\tilde{q}),B(\tilde{q})$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\tilde{q})$
\end_inset

 and other guesses.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{I}^{A},z_{I}^{B}$
\end_inset

 by policy function iteration method used in Kaplan & Moll's HACT papers.
 Do we think such a fixed point exists? Yes: we are essentially solving
 for the value of how much a firm would want to invest if creative destruction
 were exogenous and given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 and wages were exogenous and given by 
\begin_inset Formula $w(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

.
 This is a well-defined problem which has the HJB, so no reason to think
 it won't converge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Finding 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{I}^{A}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 is harder with the new setup - there is no explicit expression for it.
 However, we can use some method to find a solution to the FOC.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve individual entrant problems: compute 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{E}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{E}^{0}(\tilde{q})$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\tilde{q},0)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Given assumptions, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{E}(\tilde{q},m)=\xi$
\end_inset

 as long as 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\overline{z}_{E}^{0}(\tilde{q})/z_{E}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Check consistency of aggregate variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\tilde{q},m),\sigma(\tilde{q}),w(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 by updating to new 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,\sigma$
\end_inset

 values according to (defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}(\tilde{q},m)=z_{E}(\tilde{q},m)+z_{I}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}_{E}(\tilde{q},m)=\min(m(\tilde{q}),m\xi)$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Check consistency of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\tilde{q},m)=\big(\chi_{I}z_{I}(\tilde{q},m)+\chi_{E}z_{E}(\tilde{q},m)\big)\phi(\overline{z}(\tilde{q},m))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Public domain free-entry condition: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{z}_{E}A((1+\lambda)\tilde{q},0)=wR_{E}(\tilde{z}_{E},\tilde{q})=w\tilde{z}_{E}\phi(F\tilde{z}_{E})$
\end_inset

, which becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A((1+\lambda)\tilde{q},0)=w\phi(F\tilde{z}_{E})
\]

\end_inset

(guaranteed to hold for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{z}_{E}$
\end_inset

, and same 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{z}_{E}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}$
\end_inset

 as well) and set 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{+}=F\tilde{z}_{E}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
R&D labor indifference condition: 
\begin_inset Formula $w(\tilde{q},m)=\tilde{\beta}-\nu\tilde{A}((1+\lambda)\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If not converged, go to step (1ai) with new guesses for these aggregate
 variables.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,\sigma,z_{I}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

, compute stationary joint distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(q,m)$
\end_inset

.
 Two ways to do this:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve Kolmogorov Forward partial differential equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Simulate the economy for many periods starting with some initial distribution
 and policy rules computed above, and then numerically approximate the resulting
 distribution (probably easier).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Update growth rate using 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\lambda(\int_{0}^{\infty}\sigma(q)\mu(q,0)dq+\int_{0}^{\infty}\tau(q,m)\mu(q,m)dqdm$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If not converged, go to step (2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally, check labor market clearing: 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{F}+L^{I}(L^{F})+L^{RD}(L^{F})=1$
\end_inset

.
 If excess demand for labor, lower 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{F}$
\end_inset

 and return to step 1.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Computer Algorithm 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Guess a growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Guess an R&D labor allocation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}(q,m)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset bibtex
LatexCommand bibtex
btprint "btPrintAll"
bibfiles "sources"
options "plain"

\end_inset


\end_layout

